Java Collection Framework (JCF) is a set of classes and interfaces that provide ready-made data structures to store and manipulate groups of objects efficiently.

Java provides collection interfaces like List, Set, Map, and Queue, with ready-made classes such as ArrayList, HashSet, HashMap, and PriorityQueue, so you don’t have to write data-handling code from scratch.
The Collection Framework improves productivity by making code more reusable, maintainable and faster to develop.

Example: This demonstrates how to create, add elements to, and iterate over an ArrayList using the Java Collections Framework.

import java.util.*;  
public class Geeks {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
        // Creating a List of Strings using ArrayList (dynamic array)
        List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
        
        // Adding elements to the ArrayList
        list.add("Java");
        list.add("Python");
        list.add("C++");
        System.out.println("Programming Languages:");
        
        // Enhanced for-loop to iterate through the list
        for (String lang : list) {
            System.out.println(lang);
        }
    }
}

Output
Programming Languages:
Java
Python
C++

Explanation
Imports the java.util package to use collection classes like List and ArrayList.
Creates a List<String> using ArrayList to store programming language names dynamically.
Adds elements (Java, Python, C++) to the list using the add() method.
Uses an enhanced for-loop to iterate through the list and print each element.

Core Interfaces
The foundation of the Collections Framework is built on interfaces like Collection, List, Set, Queue, Deque and Map.They define the behavior of different collection types and serve as a blueprint for implementations.

Iterable Interface
The Iterable interface is the topmost interface in the Collections Framework hierarchy. It enables objects to be traversed one by one using the enhanced for-loop.
Package: java.lang
Key method: Iterator<T> iterator();

Any class that implements Iterable can be iterated using a for-each loop.
Hierarchy

Iterable
    ↑
Collection

The Collection interface extends Iterable, which is why all standard collections can be iterated easily

Collection Interface
The Collection interface is the root interface of the Collections Framework (except Map). It represents a group of objects known as elements.
Package: java.util
Common methods: add(), remove(), size(), isEmpty(), iterator()
It provides basic operations common to all collections.

List
The List interface provides an ordered collection that allows duplicates. Here are its common implementations:
ArrayList: Implements a dynamically resizing array. It provides fast random access but can be slow for insertions and deletions in the middle.
LinkedList: Implements a doubly-linked list. It allows for fast insertions and deletions but provides slower access compared to ArrayList.
Vector: A thread-safe, dynamic array implementation. It is a legacy class and is generally not recommended for new projects. Instead, use ArrayList.
Stack: Implements the stack data structure following the Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) principle. This is also a legacy class, and ArrayDeque is recommended for stack operations in modern applications.
Vector and Stack methods are synchronized to support multi-threading. This prevents concurrent modification issues but adds overhead. If your application is single-threaded, using ArrayList (or ArrayDeque for stack operations) is faster and more efficient.

Set
A set is a collection that doesn't allow duplicate elements. The Set interface has the following common implementations:
HashSet: Implements the set interface using a hash table. It does not guarantee the order of elements but offers fast lookups and insertions.
TreeSet: Implements a set that is sorted based on natural ordering or a comparator. It uses a self-balancing binary tree (like a red-black tree).
LinkedHashSet: Implements a set that maintains the order of insertion using a doubly linked list while still offering fast lookups like HashSet.

Queue
A queue follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO) principle. Common implementations include:
LinkedList: In addition to being a List, LinkedList implements the Queue interface, making it suitable for FIFO operations.
ArrayDeque: A resizable array that implements both the Queue and Deque interfaces. It allows efficient insertion and removal from both ends.
PriorityQueue: Implements a priority queue that processes elements based on their priority (not strictly FIFO). It uses a priority heap to order elements.

Deque
A deque java (double-ended queue) allows adding and removing elements from both ends. It is an extension of the Queue interface:
LinkedList: Implements a Deque as well as a List, allowing operations at both ends.
ArrayDeque: A resizable array implementation of the Deque interface, offering better performance compared to LinkedList in most cases.

Map
A Map java stores key-value pairs, where each key maps to exactly one value. Common Map implementations include:
HashMap: Implements the Map interface using hashing. It provides fast access to values based on keys but does not maintain the order of insertion.
TreeMap: Implements the Map interface using a self-balancing binary tree. It maintains the keys in a sorted order.
LinkedHashMap: Similar to HashMap, but it maintains the insertion order of the keys.

Collections Class (Implementations of Basic Algorithms)
The Collections class is a utility class that provides several useful algorithms to manipulate collections, including sorting, searching, and finding maximum or minimum elements. Here are some key methods in the Collections class:
binarySearch(List<?> list, T key): Performs a binary search on a sorted list to find the position of a specified element.
sort(List<T> list): Sorts the elements of the list in their natural order or based on a comparator.
max(Collection<? extends T> coll): Returns the maximum element in a collection according to the natural ordering of its elements.
min(Collection<? extends T> coll): Returns the minimum element in a collection according to the natural ordering of its elements.
reverse(List<?> list): Reverses the order of the elements in a list.
fill(List<? super T> list, T obj): Replaces all elements in a list with the specified element.

Advantages of the Java Collections Framework
Reduces Programming Effort: The framework provides pre-built, high-performance data structures, allowing developers to focus on the business logic instead of re-implementing basic data structures and algorithms.
Increases Performance: By using optimized implementations of common data structures, the collection framework ensures better performance and scalability for most applications.
Consistent API: The Collection and Map interfaces offer a uniform API for all collection classes, making it easier to work with different types of collections. The ability to sort and search collections efficiently helps in solving problems more effectively.
Improved Code Quality: Since the collection classes are well-tested and optimized, they improve the quality of your code by minimizing bugs related to data structures.
